Introduction¶

This project is an analysis of the TMDB movies dataset which contains more than 10,000 records and a plethora of information about each movie.

We will attempt to find trends of different movie properties and how they have changed over the years. We will also attempt to find the correlations -if any- between revenue and these properties. I am using revenue as the base of my analysis as this would be the most logical reason an analysis such as this would be valid in a real world scenario.

Questions to answer:¶

  1. Which movie generated the highest / lowest profits?

  2. Which genres are most popular from year to year?

  3. What kind of properties are associated with movies that have high revenues and high profits?

  4. Which production companies produced the most movies over the years?

  5. Which actors have the most movie appearances?

At first glance, the head of the dataset provides some ideas for cleaning the data:

  • There are some columns that are probably irrelevant for the purpose of this analysis
  • Data in columns budget_adj and revenue_adj is displayed as scientific notation, which is not easy to read
  • Data in columns production_companies and genres consist of multiple values separated by |
  • There are some zero values in budget, revenue, budget_adj, and revenue_adj. We need to convert these values to NaN and do a uniform drop for all of them.

Data Cleaning¶

In this section, we are going to perform the following operations on our dataset:¶

  1. Dropping irrelevant columns

  2. Dropping duplicate rows

  3. Changing the type of release_date column into datetime format

  4. Replacing 0 values with NaN, then dropping rows with NaN values

  5. Adding profit column that is the difference between revenue_adj and budget_adj

In [8]:
df.drop(['id', 'imdb_id', 'homepage', 'tagline', 'keywords', 'overview', 'budget', 'revenue'], axis=1, inplace=True)
df.shape
Out[8]:
(10866, 13)

At first glance, dropping budget and revenue columns may look like a mistake. However, these columns are redundant and misleading for the purpose of our analysis as they provide values that do not compare well across the span of production years. So we will drop them and rely on budget_adj and revenue_adj columns for comparable values.

In the above cell, I sorted the dataset by profit in descending order, then extracted the 10 highest profitable movies into¶
a mask, then created and customized a plot to show the profits for them side-by-side.¶

Research Question 2: Which genres are most popular from year to year?¶

In [22]:

In [23]:

plt.title('Most Popular Genres From Year To Year', fontsize=24)
plt.xlabel('Genres', fontsize=15)
plt.ylabel('Number Of Movies')
plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize= 14)
plt.show()
Looking at the above graph, it is easy to conclude that the 5 most popular genres are: drama, comedy, thriller, action, and adventure respectively.¶
On the other hand, genres such as TV movies, foreign movies, documentaries, western, and musicals are the least popular movie genres over the years.¶

Research Question 3: What kind of properties are associated with movies that have high revenues and profits?¶

In [24]:
plt.figure(figsize=(15,5))
corr = df.corr()
sns.heatmap(corr, cmap="YlGnBu", annot=True)
plt.show()
In [25]:
g = sns.PairGrid(df)
g.map(sns.scatterplot);
As we can see from the above graph, the properties with the biggest correlation to high profits / revenues, respectively, are:¶
1. Vote counts¶
2. Popularity¶
3. Budget¶

This shows that movies with bigger budgets are more likely to generate higher revenues and, naturally, higher profits. The correlation between the success of a movie at generating profits and its budget is feasible, given than higher budgets usually contain higher allocation to advertisement than movies with lower budgets.

Important note: The high correlation between profit and revenue of a particular movie is expected, provided that production companies usually don't go overboard with a budget to make a non-profitable movie.

Other correlations between properties of a movie are, to some degree, apparent in the above graph. The most notable ones being. These correlations are expected, as these properties have the strongest correlations with revenues and profits:¶
1. Rating (vote counts) and popularity¶
2. Budget and vote counts¶
3. Budget and popularity¶
It appears that a movie's release year, runtime, and rating (votes average) have no correlation to a movie's profitability.¶
There is also no correlation between the movie runtime and its rating¶

Conclusions¶

  1. There most popular genres throughout the years are drama, comedy, thriller, action, adventure, and romance, respectively
  2. Vote counts have more correlation to revenue than the actual rating (vote average) of movies. This can be a result of movies with higher budgets being able to generate hype through more advertisement, thus resulting in more people watching the movie and as a by-product, creating more vote counts for it.
  3. Movies with higher budgets have a better changce of generating more revenues.
  4. A movie's release year does not seem to have any effect on its revenue or profitability.
  5. Movie budgets are increasing over the years.
  6. Vote counts are increasing over the years.
  7. Runtime does not seem to have a correlation with profitability.

Limitations¶

  1. The findings are not ironclad, it is based on the information provided by the dataset and could differ, for example if other variables were introduced.
  2. Dropped values could have changed findings drastically, especially as the number of movie records (rows) that was dropped due to missing values is significantly higher than the records used in this analysis.
